Assignment 2

Air Quality

Air pollution is one of the worlds largest health and environmental challenges. Air pollution expands in two contexts: indoor (household) air pollution and outdoor air pollution.

Air pollution is often defined as the combination of outdoor and indoor particulate matter and ozone. It is a risk factor for many of the leading causes of death, including heart disease, stroke, lower respiratory infections, lung cancer, diabetes, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) (Ritchie and Roser 2019).

From https://ourworldindata.org/air-pollution

Unfortunately, over half of the worlds population lives without the protection of adequate air quality standards.

Here at home, the air quality outdoors has gotten better since the 1990s, but there are still numerous challenges in safeguarding Americans from air quality issues.

The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) regulates six pollutants as criteria air pollutants using human health-based and environmentally-based criteria.

  • ground-level ozone (OZ)

  • particle pollution (PM2.5 and PM10)

  • carbon monoxide (CM)

  • lead total suspended particulate (TSP)

  • nitrogen oxides (NO2)

  • sulfur dioxide (SD)

PM2.5 the invisible killer

Among all air pollutants, PM2.5 kills the most people worldwide. It consists of particles smaller than 2.5 microns small enough that billions of PM2.5 can fit inside a single red blood cell. PM2.5 is responsible for an estimated 4.2 millionpremature deathsevery year globally. This includes over a million deaths in China, over half a million in India, almost 200,000 in Europe, and over 50,000 in the United States (McGill University 2021).

Analytics to the rescue

Like any other data-driven decision making problem, we can tackle the challenges of air quality using advanced analytics. Business analytics can provide practical insights and aid in the decision-making of strategic decisions concerning air quality and its corresponding health-related issues.

To do so, we intend to create a complete visual analytics tool to analyze, monitor, and forecast air quality for San Diego County.

Question 1: Correlation heatmap/matrix

  • Firstly, we should summarize our correlation analysis from Assignment 1. The best approach to display (linear) correlation between multiple variables is to create a correlation heatmap (also called correlation matrix). Correlation heatmaps are heatmaps with the set of variables we analyze on the x and y-axis, and the heatmap values are the correlation between the row-column pair.

  • Write a code to create a correlation heatmap between the six pollutants of CM, SD, NO2, OZ, PM10, and PM2.5. Your visualization must:

    • Include proper axis labels, title, legend title, and source (remember we get our air pollution data from the RAQSAPI package A Simple Interface to the US EPA Air Quality System Data Mart API).

    • The coloring scale should be set to a color palette from the viridis package.

#selecting the interested pollutants (excluding TSP)

pollutants <- aq_data_Riyasha %>%
  select(CM,SD, NO2, OZ, PM10, PM2.5)

#calculating the correlation matrix and ignore rows with missing values

cor_matrix <- cor(na.omit(pollutants))

#creating the correlation heat map

p <- ggcorrplot(cor_matrix, 
                lab = TRUE,  
                colors = viridis(5),  
                title = "Correlation Heatmap of Pollutants",
                legend.title = "Correlation") +
                labs(x = "Pollutants",
                     y = "Pollutants",  
    caption = "Source: RAQSAPI package  US EPA Air Quality System Data Mart API")  
p

  • What can you conclude from this correlation heatmap? Write a brief sentence or two to elaborate.
  • The correlation heat map shows that PM2.5 and PM10 have a strong positive correlation (0.87) which means that they increase or decrease together. We can also see that OZ has a weaker correlation with NO2 (-0.63) and SD(-0.02). Overall, we can say that some pollutants seem to be strongly linked, while others are not.

Question 2: Safe levels of PM2.5

  • According to the World Health Organization (WHO), the recommended level of PPM2.5 (based on 2021 air quality guidelines) is 15 micrograms per cubic meter. Write an R code to create a chart with the following specifications:

    • A column chart with the date on the x-axis and a new column labeled PM2.5 Baseline on the y-axis. This new variable is simply defined as the PM2.5 level minus 15 (the WHO recommended level).

    • The columns of the column chart should be colored (filled) appropriately (e.g., darkolivegreen and firebrick) to indicate safe and unsafe levels.

    • Your chart should be faceted based on different sites, as the PM2.5 measurements differ per site. If a particular site does not include any PM2.5 measurements, it should not appear in your final chart.

    • Your chart should include proper axis labels, title, legend title, and source (remember we get our air pollution data from the RAQSAPI package A Simple Interface to the US EPA Air Quality System Data Mart API).

#creating a new column called PM 2.5_Baseline and removing rows where PM 2.5 is missing also creating a column for the levels

  
aq_data_Riyasha <- aq_data_Riyasha %>%
  filter(!is.na(`PM2.5`)) %>%
  mutate(PM2.5_Baseline = `PM2.5` - 15,
         Level = ifelse(`PM2.5_Baseline` <= 0, "Safe", "Unsafe"))

#creating the column chart using the new column created and facet

p <- ggplot(aq_data_Riyasha, aes(x = date, y = `PM2.5_Baseline`, fill = Level)) +
  
geom_col() +
  
scale_fill_manual(values = c("Safe" = "darkolivegreen", "Unsafe" = "firebrick"))+
  
labs(title = "Safe and Unsafe PM2.5 Levels by Site",
       x = "Date", 
       y = "PM2.5 Baseline", 
       fill = "Level", 
       caption = "Source:RAQSAPI package  US EPA Air Quality System Data Mart API") +
      facet_wrap(~ site_number)

p

  • What can you conclude from this chart? Are there any particular site or time of the year that should be highlighted? Write a brief sentence or two to elaborate.

  • From the chart we can say that around April there tends to be higher occurrence of unsafe air. This tells us that the air quality is bad around April for sits like 1026, 1022 and 1026. We can also see that site 1014 has the most red bars compared to the other sites which suggests that the air quality is poor throughout the year for this site.
